hands_on_practices.problem:
A homogeneous, isotropic, linearly elastic solid is subjected to an in-plane loading under plane stress conditions. In the small-strain regime, the in-plane strain tensor is constructed from the measured normal strains and engineering shear strain as follows: the tensorial shear component is one half of the engineering shear. For a given state, the measured components are $\varepsilon_{xx}=0.003$, $\varepsilon_{yy}=-0.001$, and $\gamma_{xy}=0.004$. Consequently, the in-plane strain tensor is
$$
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\begin{pmatrix}
\varepsilon_{xx} & \gamma_{xy}/2 \\
\gamma_{xy}/2 & \varepsilon_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
0.003 & 0.002 \\
0.002 & -0.001
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
According to the principle of strain equivalence in isotropic damage modeling with a tension-compression split, only the positive (tensile) parts of the strain tensor should contribute to the damage-driving quantity. Using spectral decomposition, compute the spectral positive part $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}^{+}$ of $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$, obtained by setting the negative principal strains to zero and reconstructing with the associated projectors. Then, using a scalar driving equivalent strain that is rotationally invariant, depends only on tensile principal strains, and reduces to the axial strain in uniaxial tension, evaluate the driving equivalent strain for this state.

Report the final equivalent strain as a dimensionless number rounded to four significant figures. Do not include units in your final answer.
